<node id="PET">
  <data key="d0">PET</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Positron Emission Tomography (PET) is a nuclear medicine imaging technique and a type of tomographic imaging that employs positron-emitting radioisotopes to create images of the body. In PET, positrons (β+) are annihilated, and the resulting 511 keV γ-rays are detected to record images. PET is utilized to measure activity in organs such as the brain and heart, and in tumors, particularly regarding glucose metabolism. PET was developed by 조장희 박사 from UCLA in 1975.&lt;SEP&gt;PET is a diagnostic imaging technique used for cancer diagnosis, often integrated with CT in PET/CT scans to enhance diagnostic accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1f7b7855d5cca22ae703580be0fcfc7f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72590c67e60a69d417d259ef71baaf90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-07321f301db639ed7357619e9557e638&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fda9da9d7fcaa192c940b687cf738dd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bc0ff97fcbf2499d0f352a78d92492f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-83b2ddf22a61c92feb5b93c9cf9b98eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-04bcfb8da445fd49f5c837b6179c61bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40baa4661c23d2fbeffe4480b2d4ce8e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0782c64fcf3afb545cd9c3f803922e58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eb74ec9701cca8844ee19c555b60135b</data>
