<node id="99mTc">
  <data key="d0">99mTc</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">99mTc, also known as technetium-99m, is a metastable nuclear isomer of technetium-99 and a radioactive isotope commonly employed as a radiopharmaceutical in nuclear medicine for in vivo studies. It is produced by a generator from its parent radionuclide, 99Mo. 99mTc has a half-life of approximately 6 hours (specifically, 6.03 hours). It decays by emitting a single gamma ray with an energy of around 140-141 keV (kiloelectron volts); one description lists the energy as 141 keV (87.9%). The Rhm value is 0.077. In 99mTcO4- solution, the concentration of 99mTc should be less than 0.5mg per 740 MBq (20 mCi).&lt;SEP&gt;An isotope with a specific energy level.&lt;SEP&gt;99mTc is a commonly used nuclide that is inexpensive but has reproducibility issues.&lt;SEP&gt;99mTc is a radioactive substance that can be used for measurement.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-924d4e084e2a6643308b6bc76af06895&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fd28894fc7b2a8aeb26f735075d67fb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-35a6e76b25728f999d21671d0895170a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dfe1a1928a0c8fd37b6094e61031eb3b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ae44ccfebfa3151a87d3796eb87d286e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dadb2dd7986d02d7bbf1f38dea49af99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2d69adcec116d52c682eb46b43c5af2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73fd9633bf193d21c88e0cf35c08d9fa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6275b489d31d3ddb70252ffd8be243b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd9b2058fcee8557f56b570183925ebd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-34f62ef495ef155167a515f56fca8173</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523347</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="18F">
  <data key="d0">18F</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">18F is a radioisotope employed in nuclear medicine for *in vivo* studies and Positron Emission Tomography (PET) imaging. As a proton emission nuclide, 18F is produced by a Cyclotron. It has a half-life of 110 minutes and emits beta+ particles (positrons) or beta+ radiation. This radiation is utilized in tumor imaging, as well as myocardial and cerebral glucose metabolism studies. 18F is also described as a chemical compound and an isotope used in medical imaging, specifically with ultra high energy collimators. It is also noted to be related to N (Nitrogen). As a radiopharmaceutical that emits positrons, 18F is valuable in PET scanning.&lt;SEP&gt;18F is a radioactive nuclide with a half-life of 110 minutes, used in 18F-FDG for sugar metabolism.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-428583e70d87d887ad563511e218180d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d83407b553bdad56b98cf8fd5be64bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d2560261ba3aefb8f27a0ce13326a00d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-924d4e084e2a6643308b6bc76af06895&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dadb2dd7986d02d7bbf1f38dea49af99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73fd9633bf193d21c88e0cf35c08d9fa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-130264f031a5f67121c20eb9f791ffb6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5c780a124da5a0a162247f1f1afa55b8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40baa4661c23d2fbeffe4480b2d4ce8e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523310</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="In Vitro Study">
  <data key="d0">In Vitro Study</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">In Vitro Study refers to nuclear medicine examinations conducted outside of a living organism, often using 125I.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775522905</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="125I">
  <data key="d0">125I</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">125I is a radioactive isotope commonly used in nuclear medicine, particularly in in vitro studies and sample testing. It emits 35 keV gamma rays through electron capture and has a half-life of 60 days. 125I is widely utilized for labeling, especially in in-vitro tests like radioimmunoassay (RIA). It can also create carrier-free labeled compounds with high specific activity. Furthermore, 125I is a substance included in liquid samples measured by a Well type scintillation counter.&lt;SEP&gt;Radioisotope produced in a nuclear reactor.&lt;SEP&gt;125I는 아이오딘의 방사성 동위원소이다.&lt;SEP&gt;125I has an Rhm value of 0.25.&lt;SEP&gt;An isotope with a specific energy level.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d83407b553bdad56b98cf8fd5be64bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5cc4f3cae46ab52d7568311ee83cce87&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1361a0035ac4f0205b268905baaa03f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-06409f405ed68573d707ceaadba57801&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-924d4e084e2a6643308b6bc76af06895&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-01aeb670194fbaa7323582a61264ce3a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2a8d3df39b55d27db11892fbbfe761c8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fda9da9d7fcaa192c940b687cf738dd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fd28894fc7b2a8aeb26f735075d67fb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ae44ccfebfa3151a87d3796eb87d286e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73fd9633bf193d21c88e0cf35c08d9fa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6275b489d31d3ddb70252ffd8be243b7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Radio Therapy">
  <data key="d0">Radio Therapy</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Radio Therapy involves using radioisotopes like 131I for therapeutic purposes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775522905</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="131I">
  <data key="d0">131I</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">131I is a radioisotope of iodine used in various medical applications, including radio therapy within nuclear medicine. It is specifically used in the treatment of thyroid cancer, hyperthyroidism, and thyroid tumors.

131I is a nuclide produced by the Hanaro reactor and other nuclear reactors for nuclear medicine testing and therapeutic purposes. It has a half-life of 8 days and emits beta rays at 606 KeV for therapeutic use. It also emits gamma rays at 364 KeV, which are used for diagnostic purposes.&lt;SEP&gt;131I is a commonly used radiopharmaceutical.&lt;SEP&gt;An isotope with a specific energy level that emits beta and gamma rays.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72590c67e60a69d417d259ef71baaf90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-428583e70d87d887ad563511e218180d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2a8d3df39b55d27db11892fbbfe761c8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fda9da9d7fcaa192c940b687cf738dd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fd28894fc7b2a8aeb26f735075d67fb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e10d247e7c97528d1ea50ec0eb927f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2d69adcec116d52c682eb46b43c5af2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73fd9633bf193d21c88e0cf35c08d9fa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6275b489d31d3ddb70252ffd8be243b7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523204</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anatomical Change">
  <data key="d0">Anatomical Change</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Anatomical change refers to structural or morphological alterations in the body.&lt;SEP&gt;Anatomical Change refers to physical alterations in the structure of the body, which nuclear medicine diagnostic methods can differentiate from functional changes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b06ed9f5e0dd9cd85ffaf0fc38757627</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775522905</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Functional Change">
  <data key="d0">Functional Change</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Functional change refers to alterations in the physiological activity of the body.&lt;SEP&gt;Functional Change refers to alterations in the physiological processes within the body, measured by nuclear medicine diagnostic methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b06ed9f5e0dd9cd85ffaf0fc38757627</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775522905</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Medical Cyclotron">
  <data key="d0">Medical Cyclotron</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A medical cyclotron is used to produce isotopes such as 18F, 11C, 13N, and 15O for medical imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Medical Cyclotron is a device used to produce radioactive nuclides for Pet imaging.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0782c64fcf3afb545cd9c3f803922e58</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523313</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="11C">
  <data key="d0">11C</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">11C is a radioactive isotope and proton emission nuclide produced by a medical cyclotron. It is a radioisotope with a half-life of approximately 20 minutes (specifically cited as both 20 and 20.4 minutes in different descriptions). 11C emits beta+ radiation (positrons) and is used in Positron Emission Tomography (PET). It's incorporated into various radiopharmaceuticals for imaging and studying processes such as amino acid metabolism, dopamine receptors, opiate receptors, fatty acid metabolism, lung function, and cerebral blood flow.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-428583e70d87d887ad563511e218180d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d83407b553bdad56b98cf8fd5be64bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-924d4e084e2a6643308b6bc76af06895&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0fd3b634121b073e3e05f1ec562accd6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fda9da9d7fcaa192c940b687cf738dd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5c780a124da5a0a162247f1f1afa55b8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40baa4661c23d2fbeffe4480b2d4ce8e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523312</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="13N">
  <data key="d0">13N</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">13N is an isotope produced by a medical cyclotron.&lt;SEP&gt;13N is a proton emission nuclide produced by the Cyclotron.&lt;SEP&gt;13N has a half-life of 10 minutes and is produced by a cyclotron.&lt;SEP&gt;13N has a half-life of 10 minutes and emits beta+ radiation, used for myocardial and cerebral blood flow.&lt;SEP&gt;13N is a nuclide with a half-life of 10 minutes.&lt;SEP&gt;A radiopharmaceutical that emits positrons, used in PET.&lt;SEP&gt;13N is a radioactive nuclide with a half-life of 10 minutes, used in 13NH3 for blood flow.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-428583e70d87d887ad563511e218180d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d83407b553bdad56b98cf8fd5be64bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-924d4e084e2a6643308b6bc76af06895&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0fd3b634121b073e3e05f1ec562accd6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5c780a124da5a0a162247f1f1afa55b8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40baa4661c23d2fbeffe4480b2d4ce8e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523310</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="15O">
  <data key="d0">15O</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">15O is a radioactive isotope and proton emission nuclide, typically produced by a medical cyclotron. It has a half-life of 2 minutes and emits beta+ radiation (positrons), making it useful as a radiopharmaceutical in Positron Emission Tomography (PET). 15O is utilized in compounds such as H215O, C15O2, C15O, and 15O2 to measure blood flow, blood volume, and oxygen metabolism, particularly cerebral oxygen consumption and blood flow in the brain.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-428583e70d87d887ad563511e218180d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d83407b553bdad56b98cf8fd5be64bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d2560261ba3aefb8f27a0ce13326a00d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-924d4e084e2a6643308b6bc76af06895&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0fd3b634121b073e3e05f1ec562accd6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5c780a124da5a0a162247f1f1afa55b8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-40baa4661c23d2fbeffe4480b2d4ce8e</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523312</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Positron">
  <data key="d0">Positron</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Positron, or 𝜷+, is emitted by proton-rich nuclides during nuclear decay.&lt;SEP&gt;A particle emitted by radiopharmaceuticals, used in PET imaging.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5c780a124da5a0a162247f1f1afa55b8</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523281</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Planar Scan">
  <data key="d0">Planar Scan</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Planar Scan is a nuclear medicine imaging technique.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775522906</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SPECT">
  <data key="d0">SPECT</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SPECT, or Single Photon Emission Computed Tomography, is a tomographic imaging technique employed in nuclear medicine. It is a method used to image the distribution of radiopharmaceuticals within the body and utilizes gamma rays. John Keys developed SPECT in 1976. In order to obtain a quantitative SPECT image, a 360° view is generally used. SPECT also involves 화상재구성 (image reconstruction) and often utilizes 99mTcO4 with a gamma camera.&lt;SEP&gt;SPECT is a medical imaging technique, which has lower resolution and sensitivity compared to PET.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72590c67e60a69d417d259ef71baaf90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1f7b7855d5cca22ae703580be0fcfc7f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-07321f301db639ed7357619e9557e638&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bc0ff97fcbf2499d0f352a78d92492f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a1e99e5d45d87bc110fb72539f81b91d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-83b2ddf22a61c92feb5b93c9cf9b98eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-130264f031a5f67121c20eb9f791ffb6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b90292f9431fa43f118e063f626e7413&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0782c64fcf3afb545cd9c3f803922e58</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523314</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Uptake Counting">
  <data key="d0">Uptake Counting</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Uptake Counting is a quantitative method used in nuclear medicine to measure the accumulation of a radiopharmaceutical in a specific organ or tissue.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775522906</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gamma Ray">
  <data key="d0">Gamma Ray</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Gamma rays (γ선) with an energy of 364 keV are used for imaging in radioisotope therapy.&lt;SEP&gt;Gamma rays have good tissue penetration and are used in both in-vitro and in-vivo measurements, particularly imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;A type of electromagnetic radiation that can be converted into visible light by a scintillator.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4f41fc508019dd2e3e10e21d1a50fac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d83407b553bdad56b98cf8fd5be64bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6275b489d31d3ddb70252ffd8be243b7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1775523225</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
